](https://www.kaggle.com/rtatman/getting-started-in-r-first-steps). ","metadata":{"_uuid":"1273cfd468efff42c3c7ca88b026d36b36b632e8","_cell_guid":"52f3936d-b721-4c2d-a926-066f7a509e02"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Your turn!\nstr(chocolateData[])\n# Use the str() function to check the data type of the columns in chocolateData","metadata":{"_uuid":"d3eca0d5daf078eb9b7346f450372def9aee7e03","_cell_guid":"5c394b81-ca26-4652-99b9-92645e4febc9","trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-05-03T14:07:52.460522Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-05-03T14:07:52.462231Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-05-03T14:07:52.485509Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-05-03T14:07:52.483591Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"tibble [1,794 × 9] (S3: tbl_df/tbl/data.frame)\n $ Company _(Maker-if_known)       : chr [1:1794] \"A. Morin\" \"A. Morin\" \"A. Morin\" \"A. Morin\" ...\n $ Specific_Bean_Origin_or_Bar_Name: chr [1:1794] \"Kpime\" \"Atsane\" \"Akata\" \"Quilla\" ...\n $ REF                             : num [1:1794] 1676 1676 1680 1704 1315 ...\n $ Review_Date                     : num [1:1794] 2015 2015 2015 2015 2014 ...\n $ Cocoa_Percent                   : chr [1:1794] \"70%\" \"70%\" \"70%\" \"70%\" ...\n $ Company_Location                : chr [1:1794] \"France\" \"France\" \"France\" \"France\" ...\n $ Rating                          : num [1:1794] 2.75 3 3.5 3.5 2.75 3.5 3.5 3.75 4 2.75 ...\n $ Bean_Type                       : chr [1:1794] \" \" \" \" \" \" \" \" ...\n $ Broad_Bean_Origin               : chr [1:1794] \"Togo\" \"Togo\" \"Togo\" \"Peru\" ...\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":14},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"This has a lot of output, but don't be scared! We'll work through it together. Your output should look something like this:\n\n![](https://image.ibb.co/eKYCK5/Screenshot_from_2017_08_29_16_09_09.png)\n\nThe first row shows you the class of the object and its size. Like I mentioned in the last section, a data_frame is a special type of data.frame called a tibble, which is abbreviated here to tbl. You can see that this tibble is 1795 rows long and 9 columns wide.\n\nIn R, the dollar sign ($) has a special meaning. It means that whatever comes directly after it is a column in a data_frame. You can use this to look at specific columns in a data_frame, like so:","metadata":{"_uuid":"2e029d6a7bfaaa1d69960b4845ea7e780364326a","_cell_guid":"0211d2ba-19ac-4c52-8e2d-cb96b48efb14"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#print the first few values from the column named \"Rating\" in the dataframe \"chocolateData\" \nhead(chocolateData$Rating)","metadata":{"_uuid":"e264a5fedcecef6609f3c5328d30bf5db7987685","_cell_guid":"a8a356c5-4a0f-4241-bea7-aa3440df8e0f","trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-05-03T14:07:21.361581Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-05-03T14:07:21.363232Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-05-03T14:07:21.390416Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-05-03T14:07:21.388037Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"<style>\n.list-inline {list-style: none; margin:0; padding: 0}\n.list-inline>li {display: inline-block}\n.list-inline>li:not(:last-child)::after {content: \"\\00b7\"; padding: 0 .5ex}\n</style>\n<ol class=list-inline><li>2.75</li><li>3</li><li>3.5</li><li>3.5</li><li>2.75</li><li>3.5</li></ol>\n","text/markdown":"1. 2.75\n2. 3\n3. 3.5\n4. 3.5\n5. 2.75\n6. 3.5\n\n\n","text/latex":"\\begin{enumerate*}\n\\item 2.75\n\\item 3\n\\item 3.5\n\\item 3.5\n\\item 2.75\n\\item 3.5\n\\end{enumerate*}\n","text/plain":"[1] 2.75 3.00 3.50 3.50 2.75 3.50"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":13},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"So all the text that comes after each dollar sign ($) here is just telling you that that's a column and it has that specific name. If you count them, you can see that there are 9 columns, just like it says in the first row of the output.\n\nThe next thing we can see from this is the type of data in each column. You can see from the fact that each column has \"chr\" printed after the colon (:) that all of these columns are of the data type \"character\". (We learned about data types in the very first part of the tutorial, [here](https://www.kaggle.com/rtatman/getting-started-in-r-first-steps/). If this doesn't sound familiar you might want to peek back for a quick refresher).\n\nThe last thing we can see is the first couple of observations in each column. However, looking at these we can see that they're not all numbers. In fact, we probably want several of our columns, like REF, Review Date and Rating, to be numeric instead. We *could* convert each column using the as.numeric() function we learned in the first part of the tutorial.\n\nFortunately, we don't have to. The tidyverse has a lot of nice utility functions that can make our lives much easier. One of them is type_convert, which will look at the first 1000 rows of each column, guess what the data type of that column should be and then convert that column into that data type.","metadata":{"_uuid":"9eaec0d2790e4fca1a8014f16641dfe93f80e21a","_cell_guid":"371b7590-5415-406b-b73b-7d2ad36a8d8f"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# automatically convert the data types of our data_frame\nchocolateData <- type_convert(chocolateData)","metadata":{"_uuid":"33e4b4fef60219a671da65b042b36686a19886b8","_cell_guid":"be92ef3a-fd8a-4fbf-9394-0a6182495140","trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-05-03T14:08:55.891236Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-05-03T14:08:55.892915Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-05-03T14:08:55.936265Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-05-03T14:08:55.934312Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stderr","text":"\n\u001b[36m──\u001b[39m \u001b[1mColumn specification\u001b[22m \u001b[36m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[39m\ncols(\n  `Company _(Maker-if_known)` = \u001b[31mcol_character()\u001b[39m,\n  Specific_Bean_Origin_or_Bar_Name = \u001b[31mcol_character()\u001b[39m,\n  Cocoa_Percent = \u001b[31mcol_character()\u001b[39m,\n  Company_Location = \u00